Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Evening Circulation Supervisor, Library/Access Services *Term* Winnipeg , MB Description Job Number:A66.23Classification:Library Assistant 4Date Posted:June 27, 2023Employee Group:AESESFunding:BudgetPosition Category:Full-Time, TermProbation/Trial Period:910 working hours or six (6) months, whichever occurs firstSalary Range:$21.80 to $30.07 per hour + 6% vacation payStart Date:As soon as possibleStatus:ExistingHours:35 hours per weekDepartment:LibraryLocation:Winnipeg, MBJob Type:TermClose Date:07/18/2023Professional Areas:StaffDescription:*This is a term position until February 15, 2024*The mission of the University of Winnipeg Library is to provide and organize the educational materials necessary to effectively support the teaching, research, and other programs offered at The University of Winnipeg. The Evening Circulation Supervisor is a full-time term position within the Circulation and Interlibrary Loan (ILL) departments of the library’s Access Services unit.The primary responsibilities of Evening Circulation Supervisor are to provide the highest quality of public service at Circulation; to act as the representative for the Circulation Supervisor during evening operational hours; and to manage requests with other institutions to loan and borrow library material.Responsibilities:Checks out and checks in circulating resources and renews materials, creates, updates, revises, and renews Library patron records.Provides instruction to Library patrons on how to use the Library website to obtain services.Collects on overdue accounts, removes holds using Student Information System once outstanding fines and materials are settled.Maintains good public relations with Library patrons, answers questions and refers to appropriate service points.Provides assistance to all patrons in the location and use of information resources in print and electronic format within and external to the Library.Deals directly with patrons concerning circulation issues, resolves issues and explains Library policies, and refers complaints and broader administrative concerns to an appropriate supervisor.Collects, sorts and re-shelves resources, shelving/shelf reading the reference collection as needed and as time permits.Returns books to the mending department for repair.Provides instruction, assistance, and basic maintenance with Library technology.Carries out Library opening and/or closing procedures.Runs report of the daily financial transactions.Provides assistance with booking materials, such as videos.May create, maintain, or update correspondence, files, records, reports, and tracking systems.May assist with the maintenance of various tracking systems.May participate in developing and maintaining standards, policies, procedures, and manuals for Circulation and Shelving.Coordinates with Circulation Supervisor to determine priorities for evening Circulation shifts, supervises and directs staff and workflow during evening hours, reports evening staffing issues and absences.Trains, allocates tasks, and assists Circulation staff with problems.Manages, documents, and reports evening security and facility issues.Uses the Interlibrary Loan system to enter and track borrowing &amp; lending requests; verifies bibliographic information; reviews search results; views, builds and modifies routing lists; and submits requests to lending institutions.Tracks unmediated patron requests to ensure timely and efficient delivery of material; maintains a document supply system to ensure materials received from external agencies are distributed to patrons.Processes items for shipping to other libraries, deals directly with patrons &amp; requesting libraries concerning Interlibrary Loan issues and inquiries; resolves problems; and explains library policy.Maintains a broad working knowledge of the Interlibrary Loan department and ensures service coverage when staff are absent.Participates in projects, attends meetings and takes part in Library Committees as appropriate.Qualifications:High School Completion or acceptable equivalent;Undergraduate degree preferred;A 2 year diploma from a recognized Library technician’s program (or equivalent) would be an asset.Two years of directly related Library experience, using procedures, standards, and systems appropriate to the area;Experience with interlibrary loan and integrated library system software.Familiarity with Relais and/or WMS would be an asset.Experience with Microsoft Office.Must have considerable manual dexterity;Ability to supervise and coordinate the work of others;Ability to multitask and manage time effectively;Ability to understand and follow oral and written instructions;Ability to apply automated and manual procedures;Ability to work independently and cooperatively with others;Ability to communicate effectively with staff and faculty.An equivalent combination of education, experience, skills, knowledge and abilities may be considered.Condition(s) of Employment:Must be legally entitled to work in Canada.Available to work Monday to Thursday evenings (from 2:00-10:00 PM) and Friday during the day (usually from 9:00 AM - 5:00 PM)Note: The work described in this posting will be conducted in-person.The University of Winnipeg is committed to equity, diversity and inclusion and recognizes that a diverse staff and faculty benefits and enriches the work, learning and research environments, and is essential to academic and institutional excellence. We welcome applications from all qualified individuals and encourage women, racialized persons, Indigenous persons, persons with disabilities, and 2SLGBTQ+ persons to confidentially self-identify at time of application.The University of Winnipeg is committed to ensuring employment opportunities are accessible for all applicants. If you require accommodation supports during the recruitment process, please contact human_resources@uwinnipeg.ca.The personal information of applicants is collected under the authority of the University of Winnipeg Act and 36(1)(b) of the Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act. All personal information collected via the recruitment process is used to assess the applicant’s suitability, eligibility, and qualifications for employment, and to otherwise support recruitment activities. This information will be provided to participating members of the recruitment process. Questions regarding the collection of your personal information may be directed to the Director, HR Services, 515 Portage Avenue, Winnipeg, MB, R3B 2E9 or human_resources@uwinnipeg.ca.The University of Winnipeg has a Mandatory COVID-19 Vaccination Policy that requires all those coming to designated indoor campus spaces to provide proof they are fully vaccinated. The Policy was suspended effective May 2, 2022. However, prospective employees should know that the Policy may be reinstated in the future based on changing public health circumstances.To apply: Careers - University of Winnipeg (northstarats.com) Compensation $21.80 to $30.07 per hour + 6% vacation pay Closes: 18 July, 2023 University of Winnipeg Winnipeg , MB Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
